<p>The intentions was to deliver a self-guided, personalized, relationship-based planning experience through a web quiz that adapts to various screen sizes in order to inspire students and fulfill career aspirations. This tool also serves as an entry point for planning via personalized content, and stir curiosity for a potential modality.</p>

<h3>Indentifying Building Blocks</h3>

<p>Through the use of this supplied project brief containing research for success, content, and general functionality, we started by identifying user flow based using required content provided. This content expressed each portion of the quiz that included questions, inputs and results displayed based on answers provided by the user.</p>

<figure class="figure-site">
	<img src="{{site.imgdir}}clients/truth-collective/lego-blocks.png" alt="">
	<figcaption><small>deciding what parts make up the whole</small></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Using <a href="http://atomicdesign.bradfrost.com" target="_blank">Atomic Design</a> philosophies, we started creating white board sketches to visually identify building blocks of the interface. This process helped to assist in identifying and isolating the required content, components and patterns thereby minimizing the interface to only required elements. Building the foundation using Atomic Design philosophies allowed for a lego-like approach to ensure modularity for developers and resulting in an easily maintainable, portable and modular system.</p>

<p>This time spent preparing and planning helps developers build in isolation allowing for portability and modularity within the codebase.</p>

<h3>Wireframing & Prototyping</h3>

<p>Creating the wireframe outlining user flow was prepared in Sketch without the inclusion of visual aesthetics. With each series of questions examined helped to draft and iterate very quickly based on rounds of feedback.</p>

